<script>
const INFO_CONTENT = {
  performance: `<div class="info-panel-title">Performance</div><div class="info-section-title">Responses</div><div class="rating-block"><strong>1. Strong</strong><span>a. Operates independently, anticipates risks, and improves the workflow.</span><span>b. Seeks improvement.</span><span>c. Handoffs are turnkey; others model this approach.</span></div><div class="rating-block"><strong>2. Solid</strong><span>a. Meets expectations with normal guidance; communicates issues promptly and follows established process.</span></div><div class="rating-block"><strong>3. Needs Dev</strong><span>a. Inconsistent delivery and late risk surfacing require frequent intervention.</span><span>b. Clear plan needed to close gaps.</span></div>`,
  real: `<div class="info-panel-title">We Keep It Real</div><div class="info-section-title">What It Looks Like</div><div class="info-item">1. Facing Discomfort: Openly communicating even when the topic is uncomfortable, showing emotional openness and integrity.</div><div class="info-item">2. Honest Communication: Speaking truthfully and transparently, regardless of whether the news is good or bad.</div><div class="info-item">3. Genuine Interaction: Being true to oneself and others, without pretense or facades.</div><div class="info-section-title">Red Flags</div><div class="info-item">1. Avoids difficult conversations or waits until forced to address an issue.</div><div class="info-item">2. Softens or omits bad news; tells people what they want to hear.</div><div class="info-item">3. Puts on a different persona depending on who is in the room.</div><div class="info-item">4. Goes along with decisions in meetings but voices disagreement only privately afterward.</div><div class="info-section-title">Evidence Prompts</div><div class="info-item">1. "Tell me about a time you raised an uncomfortable issue directly with someone."</div><div class="info-item">2. "Describe a situation where you had to deliver difficult news. How did you handle it?"</div><div class="info-section-title">Responses</div><div class="rating-block"><strong>1. Transparent</strong><span>a. Consistently raises hard topics directly and early, even when uncomfortable.</span><span>b. Delivers good and bad news with the same level of honesty and clarity.</span><span>c. Shows up the same way in every setting; words and actions are consistent.</span></div><div class="rating-block"><strong>2. Reserved</strong><span>a. Generally honest but sometimes avoids raising difficult issues unprompted.</span><span>b. May soften bad news or wait for the "right moment" that doesn't come.</span><span>c. Authentic with some people or in some settings, more guarded in others.</span></div><div class="rating-block"><strong>3. Concealing</strong><span>a. Avoids or deflects uncomfortable conversations; issues surface late or via others.</span><span>b. Tells people what they want to hear rather than what is true.</span><span>c. Behaves differently depending on audience; difficult to read or trust.</span></div>`,
  ownership: `<div class="info-panel-title">We Have Extreme Ownership</div><div class="info-section-title">What It Looks Like</div><div class="info-item">1. Taking Full Responsibility: Accepting accountability even when not entirely at fault.</div><div class="info-item">2. Proactive Problem-Solving: First to take the lead in resolving problems without waiting for others.</div><div class="info-section-title">Red Flags</div><div class="info-item">1. Points to other people, teams, or circumstances when something goes wrong.</div><div class="info-item">2. Waits to be told to fix a problem rather than stepping in.</div><div class="info-item">3. Frames issues as "not my responsibility" even when they are best placed to help.</div><div class="info-item">4. Repeats the same mistakes without taking steps to prevent recurrence.</div><div class="info-section-title">Evidence Prompts</div><div class="info-item">1. "Tell me about a time something went wrong that wasn't entirely your fault, but you owned it anyway."</div><div class="info-item">2. "Describe a problem you noticed and fixed before anyone asked you to."</div><div class="info-section-title">Responses</div><div class="rating-block"><strong>1. Accountable</strong><span>a. Owns outcomes fully, including parts outside their direct control, without blame-shifting.</span><span>b. Identifies and acts on problems before being asked; often first to step in.</span><span>c. Learns from mistakes and puts changes in place so they don't recur.</span></div><div class="rating-block"><strong>2. Reactive</strong><span>a. Takes ownership of their own mistakes but is slower to own shared or ambiguous issues.</span><span>b. Solves problems once flagged, but doesn't typically seek them out.</span><span>c. Occasionally repeats mistakes without a clear plan to prevent them.</span></div><div class="rating-block"><strong>3. Deflecting</strong><span>a. Attributes problems to others, process, or circumstances outside their control.</span><span>b. Waits for direction before addressing issues, even ones in their area.</span><span>c. Repeats the same mistakes with no visible change in approach.</span></div>`,
  beyond: `<div class="info-panel-title">We Go Beyond</div><div class="info-section-title">What It Looks Like</div><div class="info-item">1. Team Support: Willingly takes on tasks outside of job descriptions to support the team and company.</div><div class="info-item">2. Proactive: Seeks out opportunities to add value and contribute in new ways.</div><div class="info-section-title">Red Flags</div><div class="info-item">1. Sticks rigidly to "that's not in my job description."</div><div class="info-item">2. Only does the minimum required to complete assigned tasks.</div><div class="info-item">3. Waits to be asked before helping, even when the need is visible.</div><div class="info-item">4. Shows reluctance or resentment when asked to step outside their usual role.</div><div class="info-section-title">Evidence Prompts</div><div class="info-item">1. "Tell me about a time you took on something outside your normal responsibilities to help the team."</div><div class="info-item">2. "What is something you contributed to recently that nobody asked you to do?"</div><div class="info-section-title">Responses</div><div class="rating-block"><strong>1. Proactive</strong><span>a. Regularly takes on tasks beyond their role to support the team or company.</span><span>b. Actively looks for ways to add value, even in areas outside their seat.</span><span>c. Volunteers for unglamorous or extra work without being asked.</span></div><div class="rating-block"><strong>2. Reliable</strong><span>a. Will help out when asked, and does so willingly, but rarely initiates.</span><span>b. Focuses primarily on their own role; occasional contributions beyond it.</span><span>c. Completes what is assigned reliably but doesn't actively seek more.</span></div><div class="rating-block"><strong>3. Minimal</strong><span>a. Sticks closely to defined responsibilities; resists work outside scope.</span><span>b. Rarely looks for ways to add value beyond their immediate tasks.</span><span>c. Shows reluctance when asked to help outside their usual role.</span></div>`,
  energy: `<div class="info-panel-title">We Have Optimistic Energy</div><div class="info-section-title">What It Looks Like</div><div class="info-item">1. Staying Positive and Focused: Maintaining a hopeful and upbeat attitude, even in tough situations.</div><div class="info-item">2. Encouraging and Motivating Others: Inspiring positivity and motivation in those around you to create a positive environment.</div><div class="info-item">3. Prioritizing Well-being: Taking care of personal physical and mental health to maintain and spread positive energy.</div><div class="info-section-title">Red Flags</div><div class="info-item">1. Becomes negative, cynical, or withdrawn when things get difficult.</div><div class="info-item">2. Complains about challenges without offering ideas or encouragement.</div><div class="info-item">3. Drains energy from the team in meetings or day-to-day interactions.</div><div class="info-item">4. Neglects own well-being to the point it affects mood, focus, or reliability.</div><div class="info-section-title">Evidence Prompts</div><div class="info-item">1. "Tell me about a tough period recently. How did you stay positive, and how did that affect those around you?"</div><div class="info-item">2. "How do you manage your own energy and well-being, especially during busy periods?"</div><div class="info-section-title">Responses</div><div class="rating-block"><strong>1. Energizing</strong><span>a. Stays positive and focused even under pressure; attitude doesn't waver with setbacks.</span><span>b. Actively lifts others up and helps create a positive team environment.</span><span>c. Manages own well-being well, sustaining energy and consistency over time.</span></div><div class="rating-block"><strong>2. Steady</strong><span>a. Generally positive, though may dip during especially tough stretches.</span><span>b. Doesn't actively drain the team, but doesn't consistently lift others either.</span><span>c. Manages well-being reasonably, with occasional periods of strain.</span></div><div class="rating-block"><strong>3. Draining</strong><span>a. Tends toward negativity or cynicism, especially when things get hard.</span><span>b. Energy or comments noticeably bring down those around them.</span><span>c. Well-being appears neglected in ways that affect mood, focus, or output.</span></div>`,
  growth: `<div class="info-panel-title">We Have A Growth Mindset</div><div class="info-section-title">What It Looks Like</div><div class="info-item">1. Curiosity and Innovation: Being curious and always looking for and contributing to innovation.</div><div class="info-item">2. Continuous Learning: Continuing to seek knowledge and skills.</div><div class="info-item">3. Adaptability: Accepting and adopting change.</div><div class="info-item">4. Welcoming Feedback: Welcoming constructive criticism to improve performance.</div><div class="info-section-title">Red Flags</div><div class="info-item">1. Defaults to "this is how we've always done it" without question.</div><div class="info-item">2. Treats their current skill set as "good enough" and shows little interest in developing further.</div><div class="info-item">3. Resists change, drags out transitions, or reverts to old methods when given the chance.</div><div class="info-item">4. Becomes defensive, dismissive, or withdrawn when given constructive criticism.</div><div class="info-section-title">Evidence Prompts</div><div class="info-item">1. "Tell me about something new you learned or tried recently, and what came of it."</div><div class="info-item">2. "Describe a recent change at work. How did you adjust, and what was that like for you?"</div><div class="info-item">3. "Tell me about a piece of feedback you received that changed how you do something."</div><div class="info-section-title">Responses</div><div class="rating-block"><strong>1. Growth-Oriented</strong><span>a. Regularly asks questions, explores new ideas, and contributes to innovation rather than just consuming it.</span><span>b. Actively pursues new knowledge and skills, even outside what's immediately required.</span><span>c. Adjusts quickly to change, often helping others adapt along the way.</span><span>d. Seeks out feedback proactively and visibly applies it to improve.</span></div><div class="rating-block"><strong>2. Developing</strong><span>a. Open to new ideas when prompted, but doesn't often seek them out independently.</span><span>b. Learns what's needed for the role but rarely pursues development beyond that.</span><span>c. Adapts to change with some time or support, occasionally needing reassurance.</span><span>d. Accepts feedback reasonably well, though may need encouragement to act on it.</span></div><div class="rating-block"><strong>3. Resistant</strong><span>a. Prefers familiar approaches; shows little curiosity about new methods or ideas.</span><span>b. Shows minimal interest in building new skills or knowledge beyond the basics.</span><span>c. Resists or slows down change, sometimes reverting to old habits.</span><span>d. Reacts defensively to feedback or does not apply it going forward.</span></div>`,
  getsit: `<div class="info-panel-title">Gets It (G)</div><div class="info-section-title">Key Questions</div><div class="info-item">1. Can the team member clearly explain their core responsibilities?</div><div class="info-item">2. Do they understand how their role contributes to company goals and customer value?</div><div class="info-item">3. Do they grasp the systems, tools, and processes required to perform?</div><div class="info-item">4. Do they show good judgment in making decisions without handholding?</div><div class="info-item">5. Do they naturally recognize problems and opportunities in their area of responsibility?</div><div class="info-section-title">Responses</div><div class="rating-block"><strong>1. Yes</strong><span>a. Intuitively grasps how the role, processes, and business fit together.</span><span>b. Anticipates downstream impact without being told.</span><span>c. Makes sound trade-offs and explains the "why" in plain language.</span></div><div class="rating-block"><strong>2. Dev</strong><span>a. Understands the tasks but misses context or second-order effects.</span><span>b. Needs translation on non-routine work; asks "what next?" often.</span><span>c. Corrects after feedback but patterns haven't stuck yet.</span></div><div class="rating-block"><strong>3. No</strong><span>a. Repeats the same misunderstandings; can't map work to business outcomes.</span><span>b. Solutions create churn for other functions; decisions feel random.</span><span>c. Can't teach the basics of their own seat to others.</span></div>`,
  wantsit: `<div class="info-panel-title">Wants It (W)</div><div class="info-section-title">Key Questions</div><div class="info-item">1. Do they consistently show enthusiasm for their work?</div><div class="info-item">2. Do they take ownership without being pushed?</div><div class="info-item">3. Do they respond positively when given new responsibilities?</div><div class="info-item">4. Are they engaged in meetings and proactive in communication?</div><div class="info-item">5. If they had another option, would they still choose this seat?</div><div class="info-section-title">Responses</div><div class="rating-block"><strong>1. Yes</strong><span>a. Leans into responsibility; asks for harder problems and feedback.</span><span>b. Volunteers for improvements; keeps a positive, owner's tone.</span><span>c. Self-initiates learning relevant to the seat.</span></div><div class="rating-block"><strong>2. Dev</strong><span>a. Completes assigned work but rarely seeks stretch or ownership.</span><span>b. Motivation fluctuates with difficulty/visibility.</span><span>c. Needs nudging to engage beyond baseline.</span></div><div class="rating-block"><strong>3. No</strong><span>a. Avoids accountability or tough work; "that's not my job."</span><span>b. Negative or resistant to change; drags on team energy.</span><span>c. Growth and feedback are met with defensiveness.</span></div>`,
